In [[Ansei]] 3 (1856), he succeeded his brother {{ill|Toda Tadaaki|ja|戸田忠明|12=draft}} after the latter’s death, receiving the court rank of [[Junior Fifth Rank|Jūgoi-no-ge]] and the title of {{ill|Echizen Province|ja|越前守|12=draft}}. As he was still young, his rule was su11orted by senior retainers such as {{ill|Mase Wazaburō|ja|間瀬和三郎|12=draft}} (later Toda Tadashi). During his rule, Tadayuki oversaw the repair of imperial mausoleums, an achievement for which he was promoted to the rank of [[Junior Seventh Rank|Jūshi-i-no-ge]].<ref>[http://www.gokoku.gr.jp/museum_b01.html Shrine Deity Toda Tadayuki] Tochigi Prefectural Gokoku Shrine</ref>
In [[Keiō]] 4 (1868), during the [[Boshin War]], he sided with the {{ill|Imperial Army (1868–1869)|ja|新政府軍|12=draft}}. Although {{ill|Utsunomiya Castle|ja|宇都宮城|12=draft}} was briefly taken by {{ill|pro-Tokugawa forces|ja|旧幕府軍|12=draft}}, the castle was recaptured with imperial reinforcements. Tadayuki fell ill and died shortly after on the 28th day of the 5th month (July 17, 1868) at the age of 22. His grave is located at {{ill|Eiganji Temple|ja|英巌寺|12=draft}} in Utsunomiya, and his posthumous dharma name is Reikōinden Jingaku Chūretsu Daikoshi.
In [[Meiji]] 2 (1869), he was posthumously awarded [[Jūshi-i|Jūshi-i-no-jō]], and in Meiji 30 (1897), he was promoted to [[Jūsanmi]].<ref>''Zōi Shokenden Zōhohanjo,'' p.8</ref> He is enshrined as a deity at the {{ill|Tochigi Gokoku Shrine|ja|栃木県護国神社|12=draft}}.
