[[File:Grave of TODA Tadayuki, Site of Eigan-ji temple.jpg|thumb|Grave of Toda Tadayuki]]
'''Toda Tadayuki''' (戸田 忠恕, also read as Tadakumi or Tadahiro) was a {{ill|daimyō|ja|大名|12=draft|12=draft}} of the [[Bakumatsu]] period and the lord of {{ill|Utsunomiya Domain|ja|宇都宮藩|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Shimotsuke Province|ja|下野国|12=draft|12=draft}}. He was the 14th head of the main branch of the {{ill|Toda clan|ja|戸田氏|12=draft|12=draft}} (Tahara branch) and the 12th head of the Toda family of the Utsunomiya Domain. Born as the sixth son of the domain lord {{ill|Toda Tadatomo|ja|戸田忠温|12=draft|12=draft}}, he succeeded his brother {{ill|Toda Tadaaki|ja|戸田忠明|12=draft|12=draft}}. His formal wife was a daughter of {{ill|Matsudaira Mitsunori|ja|松平光則|12=draft|12=draft}}, and his adopted son was {{ill|Toda Tadayuki (adopted son)|ja|戸田忠友|12=draft|12=draft}}, his cousin of the same age.
== Life ==
Toda Tadayuki was born on the 23rd day of the 5th month of [[Kōka]] 4 (July 5, 1847), as the sixth son of {{ill|Toda Tadatomo|ja|戸田忠温|12=draft|12=draft}}, lord of {{ill|Utsunomiya Domain|ja|宇都宮藩|12=draft|12=draft}}.
In [[Ansei]] 3 (1856), he succeeded his brother {{ill|Toda Tadaaki|ja|戸田忠明|12=draft|12=draft}} after the latter’s death, receiving the court rank of [[Junior Fifth Rank|Jūgoi-no-ge]] and the title of {{ill|Echizen Province|ja|越前守|12=draft|12=draft}}. As he was still young, his rule was su11orted by senior retainers such as {{ill|Mase Wazaburō|ja|間瀬和三郎|12=draft|12=draft}} (later Toda Tadashi). During his rule, Tadayuki oversaw the repair of imperial mausoleums, an achievement for which he was promoted to the rank of [[Junior Seventh Rank|Jūshi-i-no-ge]].<ref>[http://www.gokoku.gr.jp/museum_b01.html Shrine Deity Toda Tadayuki] Tochigi Prefectural Gokoku Shrine</ref>
In [[Keiō]] 4 (1868), during the [[Boshin War]], he sided with the {{ill|Imperial Army (1868–1869)|ja|新政府軍|12=draft|12=draft}}. Although {{ill|Utsunomiya Castle|ja|宇都宮城|12=draft|12=draft}} was briefly taken by {{ill|pro-Tokugawa forces|ja|旧幕府軍|12=draft|12=draft}}, the castle was recaptured with imperial reinforcements. Tadayuki fell ill and died shortly after on the 28th day of the 5th month (July 17, 1868) at the age of 22. His grave is located at {{ill|Eiganji Temple|ja|英巌寺|12=draft|12=draft}} in Utsunomiya, and his posthumous dharma name is Reikōinden Jingaku Chūretsu Daikoshi.
In [[Meiji]] 2 (1869), he was posthumously awarded [[Jūshi-i|Jūshi-i-no-jō]], and in Meiji 30 (1897), he was promoted to [[Jūsanmi]].<ref>''Zōi Shokenden Zōhohanjo,'' p.8</ref> He is enshrined as a deity at the {{ill|Tochigi Gokoku Shrine|ja|栃木県護国神社|12=draft|12=draft}}.
