{{Citation needed|date=2019th year 3月1日 (金) 14:13 (UTC)}} {{Infobox samurai | name = Toda Tadayuki | image = Toda Tadayuki(宇都宮藩主).jpg | imagesize = 200px | caption = Portrait of Toda Tadayuki | era = Late [[Edo period]] (Bakumatsu) | birth_date = [[Kōka]] 4, [[5th month|5th month]] 23rd day ([[July 5]], [[1847]]) | death_date = [[Keiō]] 4, [[5th month|5th month]] 28th day ([[July 17]], [[1868]]) | childhood_name = Sui no Suke | later_names = Tadayuki | pseudonym = Aijo | posthumous_name = | dharma_name = Reikōinden Jingaku Chūretsu Daikoshi | resting_place = {{ill|Eiganji Temple|ja|英巌寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Eiganji Temple|qq=}}, {{ill|Utsunomiya|ja|宇都宮市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Utsunomiya|qq=}}, [[Tochigi Prefecture]] | Rank = [[Jūgoi|Jūgoi-no-ge]], [[Echizen Province|Echizen no Kami]], [[Jūshi-i|Jūshi-i-no-ge]], [[Jūsanmi|Posthumous Jūsanmi]] | bakufu = [[Edo bakufu|Edo Shogunate]] [[Temple and Shrine Magistrate|Jisha-bugyō]] and [[Sōshaban]] | master = [[Tokugawa Iesada]], [[Tokugawa Iemochi]] | domain = [[Shimotsuke Province|Shimotsuke]] [[Utsunomiya Domain]] | clan = {{ill|Toda clan|ja|戸田氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toda clan|qq=}} | father = {{ill|Toda Tadatomo|ja|戸田忠温|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toda Tadatomo|qq=}} | siblings = {{ill|Toda Tadaaki|ja|戸田忠明|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toda Tadaaki|qq=}}, {{ill|Toda Tadamoto|ja|戸田忠文|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toda Tadamoto|qq=}}, Tadayuki | spouse = {{ill|Matsudaira Mitsunori|ja|松平光則|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Matsudaira Mitsunori|qq=}}'s daughter | children = Adopted: {{ill|Toda Tadayuki (adopted son)|ja|戸田忠友|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toda Tadayuki (adopted son)|qq=}} | notable_works = }}
[[File:Grave of TODA Tadayuki, Site of Eigan-ji temple.jpg|thumb|Grave of Toda Tadayuki]]
'''Toda Tadayuki''' (戸田 忠恕, also read as Tadakumi or Tadahiro) was a {{ill|daimyō|ja|大名|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/daimyō|qq=}} of the [[Bakumatsu]] period and the lord of {{ill|Utsunomiya Domain|ja|宇都宮藩|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Utsunomiya Domain|qq=}} in {{ill|Shimotsuke Province|ja|下野国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shimotsuke Province|qq=}}. He was the 14th head of the main branch of the {{ill|Toda clan|ja|戸田氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toda clan|qq=}} (Tahara branch) and the 12th head of the Toda family of the Utsunomiya Domain. Born as the sixth son of the domain lord {{ill|Toda Tadatomo|ja|戸田忠温|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toda Tadatomo|qq=}}, he succeeded his brother {{ill|Toda Tadaaki|ja|戸田忠明|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toda Tadaaki|qq=}}. His formal wife was a daughter of {{ill|Matsudaira Mitsunori|ja|松平光則|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Matsudaira Mitsunori|qq=}}, and his adopted son was {{ill|Toda Tadayuki (adopted son)|ja|戸田忠友|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toda Tadayuki (adopted son)|qq=}}, his cousin of the same age.
== Life ==
Toda Tadayuki was born on the 23rd day of the 5th month of [[Kōka]] 4 (July 5, 1847), as the sixth son of {{ill|Toda Tadatomo|ja|戸田忠温|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toda Tadatomo|qq=}}, lord of {{ill|Utsunomiya Domain|ja|宇都宮藩|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Utsunomiya Domain|qq=}}.
In [[Ansei]] 3 (1856), he succeeded his brother {{ill|Toda Tadaaki|ja|戸田忠明|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toda Tadaaki|qq=}} after the latter’s death, receiving the court Rank of [[Junior Fifth Rank|Jūgoi-no-ge]] and the title of {{ill|Echizen Province|ja|越前守|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Echizen Province|qq=}}. As he was still young, his rule was su11orted by senior retainers such as {{ill|Mase Wazaburō|ja|間瀬和三郎|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mase Wazaburō|qq=}} (later Toda Tadashi). During his rule, Tadayuki oversaw the repair of imperial mausoleums, an achievement for which he was promoted to the Rank of [[Junior Seventh Rank|Jūshi-i-no-ge]].<ref>[http://www.gokoku.gr.jp/museum_b01.html Shrine Deity Toda Tadayuki] Tochigi Prefectural Gokoku Shrine</ref>
In [[Keiō]] 4 (1868), during the [[Boshin War]], he sided with the {{ill|Imperial Army (1868–1869)|ja|新政府軍|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial Army (1868–1869)|qq=}}. Although {{ill|Utsunomiya Castle|ja|宇都宮城|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Utsunomiya Castle|qq=}} was briefly taken by {{ill|pro-Tokugawa forces|ja|旧幕府軍|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/pro-Tokugawa forces|qq=}}, the castle was recaptured with imperial reinforcements. Tadayuki fell ill and died shortly after on the 28th day of the 5th month (July 17, 1868) at the age of 22. His grave is located at {{ill|Eiganji Temple|ja|英巌寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Eiganji Temple|qq=}} in Utsunomiya, and his posthumous dharma name is Reikōinden Jingaku Chūretsu Daikoshi.
In [[Meiji]] 2 (1869), he was posthumously awarded [[Jūshi-i|Jūshi-i-no-jō]], and in Meiji 30 (1897), he was promoted to [[Jūsanmi]].<ref>''Zōi Shokenden Zōhohanjo,'' p.8</ref> He is enshrined as a deity at the {{ill|Tochigi Gokoku Shrine|ja|栃木県護国神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tochigi Gokoku Shrine|qq=}}.
