In [[Keiō]] 4 (1868), during the [[Boshin War]], he sided with the {{ill|Imperial Army (1868–1869)|ja|新政府軍|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial Army (1868–1869)|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 官軍}}. Although [[:en:Utsunomiya Castle|Utsunomiya Castle]] was briefly taken by {{ill|pro-Tokugawa forces|ja|旧幕府軍|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/pro-Tokugawa forces|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, the castle was recaptured with imperial reinforcements. Tadayuki fell ill and died shortly after on the 28th day of the 5th month (July 17, 1868) at the age of 22. His grave is located at {{ill|Eiganji Temple|ja|英巌寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Eiganji Temple|qq=}} in Utsunomiya, and his posthumous dharma name is Reikōinden Jingaku Chūretsu Daikoshi.
In [[Meiji]] 2 (1869), he was posthumously awarded [[Jūshi-i|Jūshi-i-no-jō]], and in Meiji 30 (1897), he was promoted to [[Jūsanmi]].<ref>''Zōi Shokenden Zōhohanjo,'' p.8</ref> He is enshrined as a deity at the {{ill|Tochigi Gokoku Shrine|ja|栃木県護国神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tochigi Gokoku Shrine|qq=}}.
